{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-85405c4cb00cee5e", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1000\tboth single-pass best-val modes at all three packet-loss rates.\n1001\tTable V shows the same pattern on the in-domain MAESTRO\n1002\tfile: multi-epoch best-val gives the lowest packet NMSE at\n1003\tall three loss rates, although the gains are smaller than in the\n1004\tout-of-domain speech condition and the perceptual metrics are\n1005\tless consistent. We therefore treat single-pass best-val as the\n1006\tlower-cost deployment option and multi-epoch best-val as the\n1007\toffline quality-oriented option.\n1008\t5) Metric-specific behavior: The clearest PARCnet gains\n1009\tappear in packet NMSE, which is computed directly on the\n1010\tconcealed packets and is also the validation criterion used\n1011\tfor snapshot selection. Mel-SC changes are smaller because\n1012\tthe metric is computed over the signal representation and is\n1013\tinfluenced by the large fraction of audio that was received\n1014\trather than concealed. The perceptual metrics are useful complementary diagnostics but are not always monotonic with\n1015\tpacket NMSE. For example, multi-epoch adaptation gives the\n1016\tstrongest packet-NMSE reduction on out-of-domain speech,\n1017\twhile the PEAQ and PLCmos differences between single-pass\n1018\tand multi-epoch settings are smaller. We should note though,\n1019\tthat PLCmos was trained on speech, so it might not be very\n1020\treliable for music and PEAQ was not developed for PLC\n1021\tpurposes so it likewise might not be a proper metric [6].\n1022\t6) Runtime: On a single GPU for an 8-minute out-ofdomain file at r = 0.20, frozen PARCnet concealment has\n1023\treal-time factor 0.075, corresponding to approximately 13×\n1024\tfaster-than-real-time processing. The computational cost of the\n1025\tproposed method is dominated by adaptation: one streaming\n1026\tpass with one update per packet has real-time factor 3.10.\n1027\tSince this cost is dominated by gradient updates, reducing\n1028\tthe update frequency provides a direct path toward real-time\n1029\tadaptation. For example, updating once every three packets\n1030\twould reduce the expected adaptation cost to approximately\n1031\t3.10/3 ≈ 1.03 real-time factor, before any implementationlevel optimization.\n1032\tThe two-pass and held-out-selection settings should therefore be viewed as offline or amortized adaptation procedures in\n1033\tthe current implementation: the model is adapted once per file,\n1034\t\n1035\t\fDISSEN AND KESHET: TEST-TIME TUNING FOR PACKET LOSS CONCEALMENT\n1036\t\n1037\t9\n1038\t\n1039\tSTOI (higher=better)\n1040\t0.0100\n1041\t0.0075\n1042\t0.0050\n1043\t0.0025\n1044\t0.0000\n1045\t\n1046\tpkt-NMSE vs frozen (dB) ( = beats frozen)\n1047\t2.5\n1048\t2.0\n1049\t1.5\n1050\t1.0\n1051\t\n1052\tPESQ (higher=better)\n1053\t\n1054\t0.08\n1055\t\n1056\tCausal best-val (online) (overall -1.57 dB)\n1057\tTwo-pass best-val (overall -1.78 dB)\n1058\tMulti-epoch (5 ep) (overall -2.40 dB)\n1059\tfrozen (= 0)\n1060\t\n1061\t0.5\n1062\t\n1063\t0.06\n1064\t\n1065\t0.0\n1066\t\n1067\t0.04\n1068\t0.02\n1069\t\n1070\t0.0\n1071\t\n1072\t0.2\n1073\t\n1074\t0.4\n1075\t\n1076\t0.6\n1077\t\n1078\t0.8\n1079\t\n1080\t1.0\n1081\t\n1082\tLSD (lower=better)\n1083\t\n1084\tFig. 2. Per-file TTT concealment gain over normalized file position on outof-domain LibriSpeech at r = 0.10, averaged over 40 speakers. Values are\n1085\tpacket-NMSE changes relative to frozen PARCnet, so lower is better. Causal\n1086\tbest-val has a cold-start cost near the beginning of the file because only early\n1087\tsnapshots are available, but it approaches the two-pass result by the end.\n1088\tMulti-epoch adaptation gives the strongest improvement throughout the file.\n1089\tShaded regions denote ± one standard error across files.\n1090\t\n1091\tPLCMOS-I (higher=better)\n1092\t\n1093\tTABLE IV\n1094\tPARC NET RESULTS ON OUT- OF - DISTRI