{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-93043a1889cf1d45", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1400\tlossy signal. The method requires no clean reference signal,\n1401\tno external adaptation data, and no architectural changes to\n1402\tthe underlying PLC model.\n1403\tAcross two open-source PLC backbones, one for speech\n1404\tand one for music, we showed that received-packet selfsupervision can improve concealment on the same test file.\n1405\tThe framework is effective in both non-causal and causal\n1406\tdeployment settings, and it remains useful across in-domain\n1407\tand out-of-domain signals. These results show that test-time\n1408\ttuning can make existing PLC models more responsive to the\n1409\tcurrent speaker, instrument, recording, and loss pattern.\n1410\tMore broadly, we show that PLC systems do not need\n1411\tto remain fixed at inference time. The packets that arrive\n1412\tat the receiver contain signal-specific information that can\n1413\tbe used immediately to adapt the concealer. This provides a\n1414\tpractical path toward file-adaptive PLC without retraining on\n1415\tnew datasets or modifying model architectures.\n1416\tR EFERENCES\n1417\t[1] International Telecommunication Union, “Recommendation ITU-T\n1418\tg.711 appendix I: A high quality low-complexity algorithm for packet\n1419\tloss concealment with G.711,” International Telecommunication Union,\n1420\tRecommendation, 1999. [Online]. Available: https://www.itu.int/rec/\n1421\tT-REC-G.711-199909-I%21AppI/en\n1422\t[2] J.-M. Valin, K. Vos, and T. B. Terriberry, “Definition of the opus audio\n1423\tcodec,” RFC Editor, Tech. Rep. RFC 6716, 2012. [Online]. Available:\n1424\thttps://www.rfc-editor.org/info/rfc6716\n1425\t[3] L. Diener, S. Sootla, S. Branets, A. Saabas, R. Aichner, and R. Cutler,\n1426\t“Interspeech 2022 audio deep packet loss concealment challenge,” in\n1427\tProc. Interspeech 2022, 2022, pp. 580–584.\n1428\t[4] L. Diener, M. Purin, S. Sootla, A. Saabas, R. Aichner, and R. Cutler,\n1429\t“Plcmos – a data-driven non-intrusive metric for the evaluation of packet\n1430\tloss concealment algorithms,” in Proc. Interspeech 2023, 2023, pp.\n1431\t2533–2537.\n1432\t\n1433\t[5] V.-A. Nguyen, A. H. T. Nguyen, and A. W. H. Khong, “Improving\n1434\tperformance of real-time full-band blind packet-loss concealment with\n1435\tpredictive network,” in ICASSP 2023 – 2023 IEEE International Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP), 2023.\n1436\t[6] A. I. Mezza, M. Amerena, A. Bernardini, and A. Sarti, “Hybrid packet\n1437\tloss concealment for real-time networked music applications,” IEEE\n1438\tOpen Journal of Signal Processing, vol. 5, pp. 266–273, 2024.\n1439\t[7] E. Gunduzhan and K. Momtahan, “Linear prediction based packet loss\n1440\tconcealment algorithm for pcm coded speech,” IEEE Transactions on\n1441\tSpeech and Audio Processing, vol. 9, no. 8, pp. 778–785, 2001.\n1442\t[8] J.-H. Chen, “Packet loss concealment based on extrapolation of speech\n1443\twaveform,” in 2009 IEEE International Conference on Acoustics, Speech\n1444\tand Signal Processing, 2009, pp. 4129–4132.\n1445\t[9] J. Lin, Y. Wang, K. Kalgaonkar, G. Keren, D. Zhang, and C. Fuegen,\n1446\t“A time-domain convolutional recurrent network for packet loss concealment,” in ICASSP 2021 – 2021 IEEE International Conference on\n1447\tAcoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP), 2021, pp. 7148–\n1448\t7152.\n1449\t[10] N. L. Westhausen and B. T. Meyer, “tplcnet: Real-time deep packet loss\n1450\tconcealment in the time domain using a short temporal context,” in Proc.\n1451\tInterspeech 2022, 2022, pp. 2903–2907.\n1452\t[11] S. Pascual, J. Serra, and J. Pons, “Adversarial auto-encoding for packet\n1453\tloss concealment,” in 2021 IEEE Workshop on Applications of Signal\n1454\tProcessing to Audio and Acoustics (WASPAA), 2021, pp. 71–75.\n1455\t[12] J. Wang, Y. Guan, C. Zheng, R. Peng, and X. Li, “A temporalspectral generative adversarial network based end-to-end packet loss\n1456\tconcealment for wideband speech transmission,” The Journal of the\n1457\tAcoustical Society of America, vol. 150, no. 4, pp. 2577–2588, 2021.\n1458\t[13] D.-H. Yang and J.-H. Chang, “Diff-plc: A diffusion-based approach\n1459\tfor effective packet loss concealment,” in 2024 IEEE Spoken Language\n1460\tTechnology Workshop (SLT), 2024, pp. 357–363.\n1461\t[14] ——, “Flow-plc: Towards efficient packet loss concealment with flow\n1462\tmatching,” IEEE Signal Processing Letters, 2025.\n1463\t[15] L. Diener, S. Branets, A. Saabas, and R. Cutler, “The icassp 2024 audio\n1464\tdeep packet loss concealment grand challenge,” IEEE Open Journal of\n1465\tSignal Processing, vol. 6, pp. 231–237, 2025.\n1466\t[16] A. W. Rix, J. G. Beerends, M. P. Hollier, and A. P. Hekstra, “Perceptual\n1467\tevaluation of speech quality (pesq): A new method for speech quality\n1468\tassessment of telephone networks and codecs,” in 2001 IEEE International Conference on Acoustics, Speech, and Signal Processing, vol. 2,\n1469\t2001, pp. 749–752.\n1470\t[17] C. H. Taal, R. C. Hendriks, R. Heusdens, and J. Jensen, “An algorithm\n1471\tfor intelligibility prediction of time–frequency weighted noisy speech,”\n1472\tIEEE Transactions on Audio, Speech, and Language Processing, vol. 19,\n1473\tno. 7, pp. 2125–2136, 2011.\n1474\t[18] G. Haßlinger and O. Hohlfeld, “The gilbert-elliott model for packet loss\n1475\tin real time services on the internet,” in Proceedings of the 14th GI/ITG\n1476\tConference on Measurement, Modelling and Evaluation of Computer\n1477\tand Communication Systems (MMB 2008), 2008.\n1478\t[19] D.-H. Yang and J.-H. Chang, “Towards robust packet loss concealment\n1479\tsystem with asr-guided representations,” in 2023 IEEE Automatic Speech\n1480\tRecognition and Understanding Workshop (ASRU), 2023, pp. 1–8.\n1481\t[20] J. Zhang, Z. Zhao, Y. Liu, J. Liu, Z. He, and K. Niu, “Td-plc: A\n1482\tsemantic-aware speech encoding for improved packet loss concealment,”\n1483\tin Proc. Interspeech 2024, 2024, pp. 1745–1749.\n1484\t[21] Y. Dissen, S. Yonash, I. Cohen, and J. Keshet, “Enhanced asr robustness\n1485\tto packet loss with a front-end adaptation network,” in Proc. Interspeech\n1486\t2024, 2024, pp. 5008–5012.\n1487\t[22] ——, “A front-end adaptation network for improving speech recognition\n1488\tperformance in packet loss and noisy environments,” IEEE Transactions\n1489\ton Audio, Speech and Language Processing, 2025.\n1490\t[23] A. Krull, T.-O. Buchholz, and F. Jug, “Noise2void: Learning denoising\n1491\tfrom single noisy images,” in Proceedings of the IEEE/CVF Conference\n1492\ton Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition, 2019, pp. 2129–2137.\n1493\t[24] J. Batson and L. Royer, “Noise2self: Blind denoising by selfsupervision,” in International Conference on Machine Learning, 2019,\n1494\tpp. 524–533.\n1495\t[25] D. Wang, E. Shelhamer, S. Liu, B. Olshausen, and T. Darrell, “Tent:\n1496\tFully test-time adaptation by entropy minimization,” in International\n1497\tConference on Learning Representations (ICLR), 2021. [Online].\n1498\tAvailable: https://openreview.net/forum?id=uXl3bZLkr3c\n1499\t[26] S. Kim, M. Athi, G. Shi, T. Kristjansson, and M. Kim, “Zero-shot\n1500\ttest-time adaptation via knowledge distillation for personalized speech\n1501\tdenoising and dereverberation,” Journal of the Acoustical Society of\n1502\tAmerica, 2024.\n1503\t\n1504\t\fDISSEN AND KESHET: TEST-TIME TUNING FOR PACKET LOSS CONCEALMENT\n1505\t\n1506\t[27] D. Ulyanov, A. Vedaldi, and V. Lempitsky, “Deep image prior,” in\n1507\tProceedings of the IEEE Conference on Computer Vision and Pattern\n1508\tRecognition, 2018, pp. 9446–9454.\n1509\t[28] R. Heckel and P. Hand, “Deep decoder: Concise image representations\n1510\tfrom untrained non-convolutional networks,” in International Conference on Learning Representations, 2019.\n1511\t[29] B. Mildenhall, P. P. Srinivasan, M. Tancik, J. T. Barron, R. Ramamoorthi,\n1512\t